It's worth noting that some Chiefs of Clan Campbell were laid to rest elsewhere. For instance, the [2nd Duke of Argyll](/John_Campbell,_2nd_Duke_of_Argyll) († 1743) was buried in [Westminster Abbey](/Westminster_Abbey) in London. More recently, the [11th Duke of Argyll](/Ian_Campbell,_11th_Duke_of_Argyll) († 1973) and the [12th Duke of Argyll](/Ian_Campbell,_12th_Duke_of_Argyll) († 2001) chose to be buried on the island of [Inishail](/Inishail) in [Loch Awe](/Loch_Awe), diverging from the Kilmun tradition.

#### Churchyard

The churchyard surrounding Kilmun Parish Church is a repository of numerous historically significant memorials. It features later medieval tapered slabs, alongside high-quality post-medieval headstones, predominantly from the 17th and 18th centuries. Elaborate table-tombs, intricately carved with representations of trade tools, and the Douglas Mausoleum, are also notable features.

The graveyard has undergone expansion on two occasions, first to the north and subsequently to the west, encroaching upon some of the grounds of the nearby [Old Kilmun House](/Old_Kilmun_House). The churchyard walls themselves likely date from 1818 to 1819, the period when the graveyard was laid out in its current configuration. As part of the community engagement initiatives organized by Argyll Mausoleum Ltd, several sections of the graveyard have been meticulously surveyed, and the inscriptions on the gravestones have been recorded. Photographic documentation of most of the headstones has also been completed.

[Old Kilmun House](/Old_Kilmun_House) is situated just beyond the northwestern edge of the cemetery, with a portion of the graveyard occupying some of its former gardens.

##### Notable Burials

The churchyard is reputedly the burial place of [St Munn (Fintán of Taghmon)](/Fint%C3%A1n_of_Taghmon), the very monk whose presence established the site's spiritual significance and who is also revered as the [patron saint](/Patron_saint) of [Clan Campbell](/Clan_Campbell).

In the north-western section of the church grounds lies the mausoleum of [Sir John Douglas](/John_Douglas_(British_Army_officer)). This octagonal structure, constructed in 1888 from red sandstone, features rock-cut ashlar walls, a studded timber door surmounted by a carved armorial panel, and a stone-slabbed roof. The mausoleum serves as the final resting place for [General](/General) [Sir John Douglas of Glenfinart](/John_Douglas_(British_Army_officer)), [GCB](/Order_of_the_Bath), a distinguished military commander who served with distinction during the [Indian Mutiny](/Indian_Mutiny) and lived from 1817 to 1888.

Also interred within the Argyll Mausoleum is [John Campbell, 9th Duke of Argyll](/John_Campbell,_9th_Duke_of_Argyll), a figure of considerable historical note, who served as [Governor General of Canada](/Governor_General_of_Canada) and was married to Princess Louise.

To the north of the church, a significant figure finds her final repose: [Elizabeth Blackwell](/Elizabeth_Blackwell), recognized as the first qualified female physician in the [United States](/United_States). Her presence here adds an international dimension to the cemetery's distinguished list of interments.